<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-10-03T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-10-03T18:00:00-05:00" n="356" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d356">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6231/415: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-10-03T18:00:00-05:00">October 3, 1934—6
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>118. Your 191, October 2, noon. Commercial Attaché may say that the
                                Trade Agreements Act of 1934<note n="37" xml:id="d356fn37">48 Stat.
                                    943.</note> gives the President power to modify existing tariffs
                                only in connection with reciprocal trade agreements and that unless
                                the barter arrangement under reference took the form of a trade
                                agreement there could be no lowering of duties on items
                                mentioned.</p>
                            <p>As you know, no trade agreement with Germany under immediate
                                consideration.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>